#Q13

total_prob <- 0

# Looping through all possible values of first wave
for (i in 0:150) {
  # Probability that firsr wave = i
  prob_first <- dbinom(i, 150, 0.55)
  
  # Cumulative probability that second wave is at least 110 - i given firsr waive = i
  prob_second <- pbinom(110 - i - 1 , 150 - i, 0.3,lower.tail = FALSE)
  
  # Updating the total probability
  total_prob <- total_prob + prob_first * prob_second
}

cat("The probability ) of getting this required number of returns from both waves is",total_prob)
## The probability ) of getting this required number of returns from both waves is 0.1167226

#Q15

#a
total_cost <- function(sigma) {
  rent_cost = 10 / sigma^2
  
  # Probability rails don't meet specification
  prob_below = pnorm(0.98, 1, sigma)
  prob_above = pnorm(1.01,  1, sigma,lower.tail = FALSE)
  rework_cost = 12 * 100000 * (prob_below + prob_above)
  
  return(rent_cost + rework_cost)
}

library(stats)
result <- optimize(total_cost, c(1, 0.001))
optimal_sigma <- result$minimum
optimal_sigma
## [1] 0.007890161
cat("Standarlization of",optimal_sigma,"minimizes the annual cost of producing elevator rails")
## Standarlization of 0.007890161 minimizes the annual cost of producing elevator rails
#b
diameter_smallest <- qnorm(0.001,  1, optimal_sigma,lower.tail = TRUE)#find the lowest number in diameters
cat("one elevator rail in 1000 will be at least",diameter_smallest,"inches in diameter")
## one elevator rail in 1000 will be at least 0.9756176 inches in diameter

# Function to simulate one game
simulate_game <- function(n_spins) {
  spins <- runif(n_spins, min=0, max=1000)
  return(mean(spins))
}

# Simulation parameters
n_values <- 1:10 # From 1 to 10 spins
simulations <- 1000  # 1,000 replications for each n

results <- list()

# Simulate for each n
for (n in n_values) {
  results[[as.character(n)]] <- replicate(simulations, simulate_game(n))
}

# Visualizing the results using histograms
par(mfcol=c(12,12), oma=c(1,1,0,0), mar=c(1,1,1,0), tcl=-0.1, mgp=c(0,0,0))
for (n in n_values) {
  hist(results[[as.character(n)]], 
       main=paste("Number of spins =", n), 
       xlab="Average Winnings", 
       breaks=30, 
       col=rgb(0.2,0.5,0.3,0.7))
}



#c

#a

one_spin <- function() {
  dice_rolls <- sample(2:12, 20, replace=TRUE)
  sum(dice_rolls == 7)
}

# Perform the simulation for spins from 1 to 10
set.seed(108)  # Setting a seed for reproducibility

results <- matrix(NA, 1000, 10)
for (i in 1:10) {
  for (j in 1:1000) {
    spins <- replicate(i, one_spin())
    results[j, i] <- mean(spins)
  }
  
  # Plotting the histogram for each spin category
  
  hist(results[, i], main = paste(i, "spins"), xlab = "Number of 7's", breaks = 20, col="skyblue")
}

mu <- 20 * (1/6)
sigma <- sqrt(20 * (1/6) * (5/6))
theoretical_means <- rep(mu, 10)
sample_means <- colMeans(results)
theoretical_SE <- sigma / sqrt(1:10)
sample_SD <- apply(results, 2, sd)

# Display results
data.frame(Spins=1:10, 
           Theoretical_Mean=theoretical_means, 
           Sample_Mean=sample_means,
           Theoretical_SE=theoretical_SE,
           Sample_SD=sample_SD)

#a

mu_super <- n * 0.02
sigma_super <- sqrt(n *0.02 * (1 - 0.02))

sigma_premium <- sqrt(n * 0.01 * (1 - 0.01))

z <- qnorm(0.99)

k_super <- mu_super + z * sigma_super
k_premium <- mu_premium + z * sigma_premium

k_super <- ceiling(k_super)
k_premium <- ceiling(k_premium)

cat("For super line, there will be no more than",k_super,"defective watches being produced in an hour. As for Premium line, there will be no more than",k_premium,"defective watches produced in an hour")
## For super line, there will be no more than 18 defective watches being produced in an hour. As for Premium line, there will be no more than 11 defective watches produced in an hour
#b
watches_to_pack <- ceiling(500 + (z * sigma_premium))
cat(watches_to_pack,"watches shall be packed")
## 506 watches shall be packed
#c
expected_profit <- function(n, p_defect) {
  # Profit if all watches are defect-free
  profit_all_good <- 100 * 500 - n * 450
  
  # Expected profit if all watches are good
  exp_profit_all_good <- profit_all_good * pbinom(99, n, 1-p_defect, lower.tail = FALSE)
  
  # Expected loss when there are defective watches
  exp_loss_defect <- sum(sapply(0:99, function(x) {
    (100 - x) * (-500 - 1000) * dbinom(x, n, 1-p_defect)
  }))
  
  total_exp_profit <- exp_profit_all_good + exp_loss_defect
  return(total_exp_profit)
}

# Determine the optimal number of watches for Premium and Super lines
max_profit_premium <- -Inf
max_profit_watches_premium <- 100

max_profit_super <- -Inf
max_profit_watches_super <- 100

for (n in 100:110) {
  profit_premium <- expected_profit(n, 0.01)
  if (profit_premium > max_profit_premium) {
    max_profit_premium <- profit_premium
    max_profit_watches_premium <- n
  }
  
  profit_super <- expected_profit(n, 0.02)
  if (profit_super > max_profit_super) {
    max_profit_super <- profit_super
    max_profit_watches_super <- n
  }
}

cat(max_profit_watches_premium,"watches shall be sent from premium line")
## 102 watches shall be sent from premium line
cat(max_profit_watches_super,"watches shall be sent from super line")
## 104 watches shall be sent from super line
